@node "Intro" "File 1.0 Introduction"
@next "Shell"
@prev "MAIN"

@{b}What is File?@{ub}

An Shell or Intuition based file identification utility.


@{b}How to install File@{ub}

Drag the icon to whereever you want to put it, on hard- or
floppy-disk.  In addition, you must have FileID.library version 6 or
greater installed in LIBS: An appropriate version is included in this
archive.  If run from Workbench, File requires asl.library to be
installed in LIBS: (but everyone should have this :-)

File requires AmigaOS release 2.00 or above (Exec version 36 or
above).


Next section: @{"Shell Usage" link "Shell" 0}

@endnode

@node "Shell" "File 1.0 Usage from Shell"
@next "WB"
@prev "Intro"
Previous section: @{"Introduction" link "Intro" 0}


@{b}How to use File from Shell@{ub}

Format:   File <file | pattern>*

Template: File FILES/A/M

File will read each file passed to it and attempt to identify it.  If
more than one filename is specified, File will read the files one at a
time.  If wildcards are used, File will ID all filename which match
the wildcard pattern.  Eg to ID all the non-icon files in your
Utilities and System directories, you might type:

File sys:Utilities/~(#?.info) sys:System/~(#?.info)

If you give a directory name instead of a file or wildcards, File
will ID all the files in that directory.  Eg the following lines are
all equivalent:

File sys:Utilities sys:System
File sys:Utilities/ sys:System/
File sys:Utilities/#? sys:System/#?
File sys:Utilities sys:System/#?

File can be interrupted at any time by pressing Ctrl-C.

The results of File's identifications are echoed back to the Shell
window.  File will not open its own window when used from the Shell.
In this respect, File works a lot like the Unix "file" command, which
was my intention from the beginning :-)


Next section: @{"Workbench Usage" link "WB" 0}

@endnode

@node "WB" "File 1.0 Usage from Workbench"
@next "Bugs"
@prev "Shell"
Previous section: @{"Shell Usage" link "Shell" 0}


@{b}How to use File from Workbench@{ub}

Run File by double-clicking its icon.  File will open a window with
a readout for a filename and file identification.  Dragging an icon
into File's window will identify the file associated with that icon,
and display the filename and identification in the readout.

There are three gadgets in the window:
· "Select": this opens an ASL file selector, so you can select a file
  that doesn't have an icon for File to identify;
· "About": brings up a window with information about the program;
· "Quit": exits from the program.

Initially, File's readout will display information about File itself.
If you run File by clicking once on its icon and shift-clicking
another icon, File will initally display information on the file
associated with the shift-clicked icon.

File will always reject directory icons.  But then, why would you want
to ID a directory?  :-)

File has one keyboard shortcut: pressing ESCAPE is the same as
clicking on the "Quit" button, or clicking the window's close gadget.


Next section: @{"Limitations" link "Bugs" 0}

@endnode

@node "Bugs" "File 1.0 Limitations"
@next "Acknowledgements"
@prev "WB"
Previous section: @{"Workbench Usage" link "WB" 0}


@{b}Bugs and limitations@{ub}

FileID.library can't identify @{i}everything@{ui}, but it is pretty good.  Most
file types will be recognized.  If you have a file type which you'd
like me to add myself, contact me and I might add it.  The ASCII
recognition routine is not part of FileID.library but was written by
myself; it works most of the time :-)

It would be nice if File recognized different types of ASCII text;
eg C source file, AmigaDOS scripts etc.  But it doesn't.


